In a sensibly constructed head drawing, you should be able to "feel" the skull. Imagine you closed your eyes and you were trying to identify someone's face by touch; the first thing you felt wouldn't be the details of the eyelash or the nostrils. You would feel a bony skull with skin, muscle, and fat on it. 

To learn how to apply this concept to your artwork, please join me for my online portrait sketch workshop January 21st and 22nd. Details and registration link can be found in the linktree in my bio.

On December 23rd, I received the news that my stepdad had an accident and was on life support. The prognosis was to get on a flight immediately for the chance to say goodbye. He held on until we could all be together. The nurses looked the other way as we broke the visitation rules and all crowded into his room on Christmas. Nobody held back. My sister sang. I thanked him for taking care of mom. Mom held his hand. She called him by his nickname that she gave him the day they met. She called him her best friend. She told him it's ok if he needs to let go. He passed not long afterward.

This painting is inspired by that moment. With no reference or intention to be literal, I worked from memory and some casts from my studio. My goal was to convey an iota of the warmth and tenderness I observed. "Whispered Farewell"

Combining the past with the present has been a puzzle that has occupied me for many years. Lately I have been exploring using some of the vocabulary from the 19th century academics to react to my own experiences and observations. This unfinished crop of a work in progress will be part of that upcoming series. When finished, they will be covered in tattoos, smoking and drinking at the Oregon coast.

Also, don't miss my upcoming  anatomy and figure drawing or portrait painting workshops later this month.

Here is a sneak peek of a show that will be opening on Sunday, December 3rd at First Presbyterian Church of Portland after service at 11:30.

The show consists of a series of portraits of homeless people that were created from life with my late friend Jim Gion at High and Low Gallery. Jim had been doing sculpture work of homeless people for years, and through his good rapport with the local homeless, we started paying them to pose for quick sketches. I've never had an art show at a church before, but considering that they are doing real humanitarian work housing people it seems like the only proper gallery to show these works. The show will be hanging in their chapel gallery until January 28th. Hope to see you at the opening.
